ng|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{tt|tl|bebot}} {{qualifier|slang}}\n* Telugu: {{tt+|te|పిల్లాడు|m}}, {{tt+|te|పిల్ల|f}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|bebek}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|babi}}\n* Yiddish: {{tt|yi|קעצעלע}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|pet project}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|kindje|n}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|lapsi}}, {{tt+|fi|silmäterä}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|bébé|m}}, {{t+|fr|benjamin|m}}\n* Latvian: {{tt|lv|rūpju bērns}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|dieťa}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|barn|n}}, {{tt+|sv|ögonsten|c}}\n* Telugu: {{tt|te|మానస పుత్రిక}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|lastborn of a family}}\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|baba}}\n* Bashkir: {{tt|ba|кинйә}}, {{tt|ba|төпсөк}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|benjamí|m}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|benjamin|c}}, {{t|da|yngstemand|c}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|benjamin|m}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|pesamuna}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kuopus}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|benjamin|m}}, {{tt+|fr|benjamine|f}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Nesthäkchen|n}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|תִּינוֹק|m|tr=tinók}}, {{tt+|he|תינוקת|f|tr=tinóket|alt=תִּינֹקֶת}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{tt|kmr|axirpişt|m|f}}\n* Latvian: {{tt|lv|pastarītis|m}}, {{tt|lv|pastaris|m}}\n* Māori: {{tt|mi|pōtiki}},\n* Navajo: {{tt|nv|lókʼeeshchąąʼí}}\n* Persian: {{tt|fa|ته تغاری|tr=tah taġâri}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|benjamim|m}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|mezin|m}}, {{tt+|ro|mezină|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|benjamín|m}}, {{tt|es|benjamina|f}}\n* Swahili: {{tt+|sw|mtoto}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|minsting|c}}\n* Tamil: {{t+|ta|கடைக்குட்டி}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* North Alaskan Inupiatun: {{tt-check|ikt|[[qitunrauraq]] [[paipiraq]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|en|babeh}}\n* {{l|en|gamete}}, {{l|en|zygote}}, {{l|en|morula}}, {{l|en|blastocyst}}, {{l|en|embryo}}, {{l|en|fetus}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{en-adj|er,babyer,baby-er}}\n\n# {{lb|en|of vegetables, etc.}} Picked when small and immature (as in ''baby corn'', ''baby potatoes'').\n# {{cap|newest}} (overall, or in some group or state); most [[inexperienced]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1894|author=Marion Harland|title=The Royal Road, Or, Taking Him at His Word|page=136\n|passage=Mrs. Paull held out her hand to the '''babyest''' of the quartette, as they tiptoed up to  the bed. “Lift her up, please, Marie!” she said, motioning to the place enclosed by her arm. When the rosy cheek touched hers upon the pillow, she asked&nbsp;...}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1910|author=Marion Harland|title=Marion Harland's Autobiography: The Story of a Long Life|page=408\n|passage=That evening, we grouped about the fire in the parlor, a wide circle that left room for the '''babyest''' of the party to disport themselves upon the rug, in the glow of the grate piled with cannel coal.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=Marion Halligan|title=The Apricot Colonel|publisher=Allen & Unwin|isbn=9781741158588\n|passage=Of when I was a '''baby''' editor. Very '''baby''', it was actually a kind of work experience, I was still at university but I knew what I wanted. With a small independent publisher, good reputation, did some marvellous books, {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-book\n|en\n|year=2020\n|author=Hannah Abigail Clarke\n|title=The Scapegracers\n|publisher=Erewhon\n|isbn=9781645660002\n|page=391\n|passage={{...}} party for Halloween proper? Just the four of us and some goofy, spooky kids' movies, you know? Some cute pumpkin-shaped cupcakes? I could make my dog a little costume. He could be a baby witch. The '''babyest''' Scapegracer.” I blinked.}}\n# {{lb|en|in the comparative or superlative}} Like or pertaining to a [[#Noun|baby]], in size or youth; small, young.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1888|title=Monthly Packet|page=170\n|passage=Spider. Here  let us begin at the beginning, at the '''babyest''' of books for Edith&#39;s nursery.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1894|author=Edith E. Cuthell|title=Two Little Children and Ching|page=107\n|passage=She let it drop out of her sleeve, and it was two Chings — the dearest, littlest, '''babyest''', tiny Chings — little balls of fur! And she ran away, and daddy&#39;s father picked them up, and put them in his pockets, and brought them home, {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1908|author=Marion Harland|title=Housekeeper's Guide and Family Physician|page=98\n|passage=Lemon-juice for ink spots: Not many weeks ago the '''babyest''' member of our  household - perhaps moved by a hereditary tendency toward ink - slinging - divided the contents of an ink bottle impartially between the tiles of the bath-room floor&nbsp;...}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1908|author=Mary Findlater; Jane Helen Findlater|title=Crossriggs|page=25\n|passage=\"There&#39;s a '''babier''' baby than Mike,\" she said. \"But you will see her to-morrow. Aren&#39;t we rich? Come in and see Matilda - you won&#39;t find her much changed. It&#39;s so absurd to see her with all these children.\"}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1936|author=United States. Congress. House. Committee on Military Affairs|title=To Promote the National Defense by Stengthening the Air Reserve, Hearings ..., on H.R. 4348, 12241, Feb 27, April 22, 1936|page=31\n|passage=Now, we all believe in national defense, but we also believe in peacetime activity, and my personal idea about aviation is that it is still in its absolute “'''babyest'''” type of infancy, that it is nothing even approaching what it will be even 10 years [from now].}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Recreation Activities in City Attain New Peak in Past Week|journal=[[w:Lansing State Journal|The State Journal]]|volume_plain=eighty-third year|location=Lansing, Mich.|date=7 August 1937|section=section “Doll Show at Allen”|page=2|column=7|passage=A doll show held the attention of children at Allen as a special feature during the week. Winners were:{{...}}'''baby-est''' doll, Betty McQueary.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Charles P. Stewart|title=Washington At A Glance|journal=[[w:The Independent (Massillon)|The Evening Independent]]|volume=LXXIV|issue=130|location=Massillon, Oh.|date=22 October 1940|page=five|column=2|passage=He’ll &#91;{{w|Joseph H. Ball}}&#93; be our baby senator for the next two years. Senator [[w:Rush Holt Sr.|Rush D. Holt]] of West Virginia will be his baby rival briefly, but Rush is a lame duck. He’ll be out of the picture at the end of the year and Joe will be the '''baby-est''' of them all.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Herb Smith|title=Recreation In Cedar Grove|journal=Verona-Cedar Grove Times|volume=XII|issue=31|location=Verona, N.J.|date=4 August 1960|page=26|column=2|passage=The victorious individuals were as follows: Doll Contest—{{...}}“'''baby-est''',” 1st, Mary Grew, 2nd, Susan Shamlian;}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Liz Nicholls|title=Gala to mark Teatro’s entry into the quarter-century club|journal=w:Edmonton Journal|location=Edmonton, Alta.|date=2 August 2007|page=D3|column=1|passage=One of them, Allure Potemkin (and don’t you wish that was ''your'' name?), hikes up her slip and does a riotous dance number called ''Baby Legs''. Leona Brausen, whose own dimpled gams — “'''baby-er''' than ever” as she says — inspired the role, is back onstage Saturday to dance the dance for the last time.}}\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{cite-text|en|year=1987|author=Raphael Sappan|title=The Rhetorical-logical Classification of Semantic Changes|volume=5|page=58\n|passage=''Baby''. In its attributive uses, the word has the meaning &#39;small, tiny&#39;. In the following sentence it is a metonym, still preserving its relation to the original meaning: “There is a babier baby than M.” (in the entry ''baby'' of the first volume of&nbsp;{{...}}}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[coddle]]; to [[pamper]] somebody like an infant.\n#* {{RQ:Lewis Babbitt|passage={{...}} though he tried to be gruff and mature, he yielded to her and was glad to be '''babied'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1944|author=w:Emily Carr|title=w:The House of All Sorts|chapter=Friction|pageurl=http://www.gutenberg.net.au/ebooks01/0100121h.html\n|passage=Then the man effected measles and stayed off the job for six weeks, '''babying''' himself at home, though he lived just round the corner from my half-built house.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[tend]] (something) with [[care]]; to be [[overly]] [[attentive]] to (something), [[fuss over]].\n#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Mr. Mac and His Team|journal=[[w:Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=31 March 1967|titleurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130721111413/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,941104,00.html\n|passage=In the past 27 years, \"Mr. Mac,\" as he is known to his 46,000 teammates, has built and '''babied''' his McDonnell Co. from nothing into a $1 billion-a-year corporation.}}\n#* '''1912''', Linda Craig, interviewed by Theresa Forte, \"Tree and Twig farm — a treasure chest of heirloom tomatoes,\" ''Welland Tribune'', 25 May, 2012, [https://web.archive.org/web/20171205052150/http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2012/05/23/tree-and-twig-farm--a-treasure-chest-of-heirloom-tomatoes]\n#*: I have grown them for years and although some years are better than others, I have always had loads of tomatoes by not '''babying''' them, going easy on the water, and fertilizing with compost in the planting hole.\n\n====Translations====\n{{multitrans|data=\n{{trans-top|to coddle; to pamper somebody like an infant}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|dorloti}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|choyer}}, {{tt+|fr|dorloter}}, {{tt+|fr|pouponner}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|θωπεύω}}, {{tt+|el|κανακεύω}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|दुलारना}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|दुलारना}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|dalta}}, {{tt+|sv|pjoska}}, {{tt+|sv|klema}}\n* Tamil: {{t+|ta|கொஞ்சு}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to tend (something) with care}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n}}\n\n===Derived terms===\n{{col3|en| collodion baby|title=Terms derived from the adjective, noun, or verb ''baby''|adult baby\n|affair baby|gray baby syndrome|grey baby syndrome|baby toe\n|AIDS baby|Water Baby| baby-brained|Bartlemy baby\n|anchor baby| baby cage|baby juice|baby monster group